Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Queviante Dominique Lucas in court with attorney Jamie Francis Cimpl-Wiemer.  Defendant Queviante Dominique Lucas in custody.  Jeremy R. Arn appeared for the State of Wisconsin.  Pursuant to plea negotations, MPD incident numbers 143550023 with an occurrence date of 12-21-13 and incident report 143550028 with an occurrence date of 12-21-13 as outlined in the criminal complaint, to be used as READ-INS. Defendant changes plea to GUILTY to both counts.  Defendant examined as to his plea, advised of his Constitutional rights and the maximum penalty. Court found that defendant freely, voluntarily and intelligently waived his rights. Plea questionnaire received and filed. Parties stipulate to the complaint as a factual basis to sustain defendant's plea. Court found defendant guilty on both charges as charged in the information and ordered a Judgment of Conviction be entered on the record.  Defendant further advised that if he is not a US citizen deportation is possible.  

Sentencing proceeded.  Statements made by State, Defense and Defendant.  

AS TO COUNT 1:
The Court sentenced defendant to serve a term of IMPRISONMENT in the Wisconsin State Prisons for 5 YEARS.  INITIAL CONFINEMENT of 18 MONTHS and EXTENDED SUPERVISION of 3 1/2 YEARS, concurrent with COUNT 2, but consecutive to any other sentence, with credit for 0 days time served.
